The paper deals with distributed algorithms and their verification, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). It also involves error-correction and coding theory, which is related to Information Theory (cs.IT). The paper uses batch evaluation and randomized verification, which are techniques commonly used in Computational Complexity (cs.CC). The algorithms presented in the paper are based on graph theory, which is a topic in Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the paper deals with security and robustness against byzantine failures, which is related to Cryptography and Security (cs.CR).
